node.text:
Project of the Week: Designed by @CharlotteTaylr & @Ni.acki, Villa del Soffio is an experimental home niched in the cliffs of #Puglia. The structure acts as a bridge between both sides of the beach allowing for a generous double height space with a minimal footprint in the natural landscape. The house is composed of two slabs glazed on each side,  overlooking the raw vertical cliffs to the west and the Adriatic sea to the east.

The interior layout works as one continuous space with no interruptions and punctuated by two layers of curtains where privacy is needed. A first layer on the open mezzanine overlooking the living spaces, and a second double height layer all around the house. This project questions the relationship we entertain with our environment by reimagining the shape and foundation of the house itself. #architectanddesign

node.text:
Hagia Sophia (Ayasofya in Turkish) can be considered as the best and the most visited sights in #Istanbul together with the neighboring Topkapi Palace. 
It is a former church and museum and declared as one of the world’s greatest architectural works.

Built as a church in 325, Hagia Sophia was rebuilt in 537 and was converted into a mosque by Fatih Sultan Mehmet after the conquest of Istanbul in 1453. 
In 1935, the Hagia Sophia was established as a museum under Mustafa Kemal Ataturk and the newly established secular republic of Turkey.

Last July, the Turkish government opened Hagia Sophia to prayer for the first time in 86 years, reverting the building’s status from museum back to mosque. 📸: @thehakanarslan, @dr.iyasar #architectanddesign

This ‘invisible bridge’ is located in the West Brabant Water Line region of the #Netherlands, where inhabitants in the seventeenth century built a series of moats and fortresses to protect themselves from invasion. 

Made entirely of wood and waterproofed with EPDM foil, the bridge was built in 2010 to form a passageway to the newly restored Fort de Roovere. “It can’t be seen from a distance because the ground and the water come all the way up to its edge,” @ROADArchitecten explain. “When you get closer, the fortress opens up to you through a narrow trench. You can then walk up to its gates like Moses on the water.” #architectanddesign

Located next to the mouth of the Douro River in the north of #Portugal, #Porto is the second largest city in the country. It has 15 freguesias, equivalent to neighborhoods or parishes, and is known for its churches, trams and wine of the same name, since it houses several wineries on the banks of the Douro River. 

It is a port and dynamic city, that offers a vibrant nightlife thanks to the countless students who live there. Porto has an extensive historical heritage and in 1996, its historic center was declared a World Heritage Site by UNESCO. 📸: @scwilder #architectanddesign

Reimagined by El Fenn general manager and interior designer Willem Smit, @Riad_Les_Yeux_Bleus tantalizes the eyes with a brilliant juxtaposition of colonial and pop art touches, and a high-octane dose of color. Bold indigo, mint green and turmeric walls gracefully contrast hand-painted zellige tiles, round brass chandeliers and cedar wood carvings.

With its blend of contemporary and traditional styles, Riad Les Yeux Bleus reflects the nature of its surroundings – vibrant and sophisticated with an excellent choice of trendy bars, art galleries, and restaurants coexisting in friendly symbiosis with the ancient ways of the city. #architectanddesign

Admont Abbey is the oldest monastery in #Styria, #Austria and also holds the world’s biggest abbey library. Besides being a source for knowledge that has been handed down through centuries, the library is a masterpiece of the baroque period itself with its extraordinary architecture, frescoes, sculptures, manuscripts and printed works. 

Completed in 1776, the library holds 70,000 volumes while the abbey in total owns nearly 200,000 books. Among them are very valuable manuscripts, with some even dating back to the 8th century AD and the so-called ‘incunabula’ – books that were printed before 1500. 🎥: @madelinestraveling #architectanddesign

node.text: The Arch of Ctesiphon (Taq Kasra), located 40 km south of #Baghdad, was built in the 6th century AD. It is the world’s largest brick vault and the largest free-standing arch constructed until modern times. A part of a Sasanian palace complex, it stands at 37 meters high and 26 meters wide, making it a unique monument of great historical and cultural significance. #architectanddesign
